<br>
<br>
          ~Krakka Grinned as he smacked the younger ogre on the back.  &quot;Dat's a guud wun, Joo!  Way ta geaux!&quot;~<br>
<br>
<br>
          ~Savajj and Visya sat close together on the plains of the OT, the towering testement to the lost Iksar nation rising behind them.  Gruuz stood behind them, idly smacking one of the strange moving cactuses around.~<br>
<br>
<br>
          ~Gruuz Nodded as Caterlie spoke, telling of the history of the Warriors of the Realm.~<br>
<br>
<br>
          ~Gruuz howled with glee as he laid into the great Dragon with his mighty axe, again, and again, the other members of Lex invictus doing the same, but he hardly noticed them as the blood rolled across his vision...~<br>
<br>
<br>
     Gruuz sighed, and opened his eyes.  He needed a break.  The bickering, the animosity, the cliques that were starting to show...  He could see them all.  He had seen it before.  There was nothing he could do about it, just himself.  The only thing he could do was wait.  Either the family would recover and become tighter from its mistakes, or it would be ridden asunder from the turmoil within.  Either way, he would survive.  He would always survive.  That was the first thing Kimzak had taught him.  Survive.<br>
<br>
     He didn't want to just survive, though.  There was so much more to be had.  Kimzak was a devout follower of Cazic Thule, and Gruuz followed none.  Not one.  Rather, he worshiped none.  The fear that Cazic ingrained into his creatures...  Gruuz didn't want that.  He wanted family, friends, some one to sit down and share some Smoked Wood Elf with.  Sure, he could survive.  But he wanted more.  He wanted to live.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
     (ooc) I refuse to post a flame on the boards.  Doing so causes nothing but more of the same.  Problems don't get solved by shouting matches, and while the bickering is true to form of a real family, it can also be painful.  This is how i make my views known.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
